  "prompt": "What is the difference between a royalty and a license?",
  "response": "The terms \"royalty\" and \"license\" are related but refer to different concepts, particularly in the context of intellectual property, such as patents, copyrights, and trademarks. \n\n1. **Royalty**:\n   - A royalty is a payment made to the owner of a particular asset, often intellectual property, for the right to use that asset. \n   - It is typically calculated as a percentage of revenue generated from the use of the asset or a fixed amount per unit sold. For instance, authors may earn royalties from book sales, musicians from album sales, or inventors from patented products.\n   - The payment is ongoing, depending on the terms of the agreement, meaning that the licensee pays royalties as long as they use the licensed property.\n\n2. **License**:\n   - A license is a legal agreement that grants permission from the owner of intellectual property (the licensor) to another party (the licensee) to use that property under specified conditions.\n   - Licenses can be exclusive or non-exclusive and may cover geographical limitations, duration, and specific usage rights.\n   - The license itself can involve one-time fees, royalties, or a combination of both, and it details what the licensee can and cannot do with the intellectual property.\n\nIn summary, a royalty is a type of payment associated with the use of an intellectual property that typically arises from a licensing agreement, while a license is the legal document that outlines the terms under which that intellectual property can be used.",
